It IS a good thing. Businesses can lose a lot of money over bad optics because if they retain a bad actor, it publicly calls the company's ethics into question. They can't let one bad seed ruin their bottom line. It doesn't just affect owners and investors, it affects everyone they support with employment. If the company retains a bad actor, they lose money; loss of income means laying off workers. They can't let the actions of the bad actor jeopardize all those careers; that would be an act of bad faith on their part. They have an ethical responsibility to maintain the public's trust in their brand.

Check out the story about Megadeth firing David Ellefson for his indiscretions with a young woman. They're a band that has a reputation for having strong Christian and conservative values. Ellefson is a minister and he's married. He shit on his religion and his wife with his actions, and rather than accepting responsibility for his actions, he's trying to put the blame on the young woman and the person who leaked the video footage of his indiscretion. That makes his whole life a lie. How would that reflect on Dave Mustaine, the owner of the Megadeth brand, if he sided with Ellefson? It would make everything they say and do as a band a lie. Other bands that profess those values have suffered because of bad actors admitting it was just for show or making serious ethics violations that reflected negatively on the band. Megadeth could lose a lot of fans and money over that, at a time of severe economic depression in the music industry.

I asked Ellefson for help a number of years ago. He declined, but after losing his job in Megadeth, he might come around asking me to help him form a new band. In consideration of that, I had to release a statement on Twitter that I will have no business relations with Ellefson because of his indiscretion. Maybe not a lot of people know about my interaction with Ellefson, but it's enough to damage my reputation if those people call my ethics into question because I once asked him for help and I leave that door open. Silence in a matter can bring just as much condemnation as taking the wrong side.

@Katlyn Shute wow, that's crazy how you inadvertently were treating your symptoms at first! I do wonder if I had been doing that until the pandemic as well, but hopefully we'll see. And thank you so much! I hope you also take care of yourself in the future and learn to cope with your own mental health as well ^-^

@Char Macmillan good luck my friend!! It is very difficult to feel as if something is wrong but have no answers as to why. Or for people to tell you if you him just try harder you would be fine. The worst is being told you are just faking stuff for attention. It‚Äôs so disheartening. Mental health is so stigmatized and it makes my blood boil. Do we tell people with asthma‚Ä¶you just aren‚Äôt trying hard enough to breath. You would be fine if you just put in some effort. It crushes your self esteem when you are told your struggles are your fault. Especially when we are young. I was a 4.0 student, aged varsity sports, was on theatre, and so each team. I did so well because I was unknowingly treating my ADHD because I had such a crazy strict schedule that was meticulously mapped out each week because if I wanted to fit everything in I had to do it that way. So I unknowingly had been self treating. Then I became an adult and stuff got a lot harder because my schedule was no longer packed to the gills with all my activities plus school. After battling a sports injury that resulted in an addiction to pain killers my undiagnosed adhd was so bad and it made things very very difficult. I have sober for over 7 years which made actually made my adhd worse. The pills were also helping me manage my symptoms. pandemic made my symptoms hit me like a ton of bricks. Finally went for an evaluation and my doc was shocked that no one ever noticed it in my family. We need to make mental health and things like adhd, ocd, depression, bi-Pilar, substance abuse disorder, etc not so scary. These are not death sentences, you can still live a normal life, nothing is ‚Äúwrong‚Äù with you if you have a mental illness, you are simply different and you are no less of a person than anyone else. I think it takes so long to diagnose people because it‚Äôs so stigmatized. If people stopped the scare tactics and stop making a mental health diagnosis out to be the boogie man people would be much quicker to ask for help and save them years of suffering alone and in silence. I hope you find a diagnosis soon friend. Don‚Äôt give up, it can take time but finding out a diagnosis and getting the right treatment for you is worth all of that lain, trial, and error. If you ever need to vent or talk come back here and let me know and we can figure out the best way to connect (I‚Äôm not kidding at all. Totally serious. Sometimes just having a person to talk to makes you feel less alone. I don‚Äôt ever want anyone to feel alone or scared. No matter if I know them or not. I can‚Äôt say I can solve your problems, I‚Äôm not a doctor (I just play one on TV lol.) but I am a person,  I have ears, and I‚Äôm willing to be there to listen and support someone in need. I hope you are doing well and I‚Äôm sending you love and good energy this upcoming weekend. Happy Memorial Day, be safe, and don‚Äôt forget to take care of yourself . There is only one you and the world would be different without your shining presence on it, as happy and healthy as you could possibly be.

@William Jenkins 2nd part to my comment:

3. What studies are you referencing and where did they source their data? Because public FBI records show that more men are arrested and convicted for every crime except prostitution. Where is your claim of "more women cause more fatalities" coming from, if the numbers show that men commit most violent and nonviolent crimes?

4. When you're ready to actually care about men's liberation, consider this:

Why do you seemingly only care about which gender commits more crime, but nothing beyond that? If you cared about gender liberation, why wouldn't your first thought be to figure out why these numbers exist? What causes men to commit more crimes? What can we do to meet their needs and give them resources so they aren't in a position to commit more crime?

You're very obviously approaching this in a "men vs women, gender battle" mentality when it's not men vs women. Our focus needs to be on uniting and understanding where our needs are being failed and what we can do about it.

@William Jenkins My comments keep getting deleted, so I'll have to split it into two parts [for some reason this sometimes works]

1. It's apparent that statistics simply isn't in your area of familiarity. Numbers don't technically lie, but numbers are influenced by human bias and subject to bias present in the processes of interpretation and presentation.

So with your black crime example, numbers that float around on social media tend to be either completely made up or real numbers from authentic databases that they've kept sterile to make the interpretation that "black people commit more crime". However, if we look at these numbers within the context of the social and material realities of the black community (and American history), we get a far more nuanced, fleshed out view for why these numbers exist.

2. It's fallacious to draw the conclusion that because an institution is problematic, their numbers are automatically useless. Numbers don't technically lie, but they can leave out key points, giving you only a partial story. They can be a great place to *start*.
